marginalization of routine inflammatory parameters data on age and sex¶

The Goal of this notebook is to marginalize the effect of sex and age for each of the routine inflammatory parameters in order to account for differences in median age and sex between the patient groups when testing for significant differences.

The resulting data is the basis for figure 2 A and B

In [2]:

To investigate differences between these group, a approach similar to the one deployed on the molecular data seems appropriate (ie. marginalization on age and sex followed by statistical testing of difference in location between groups).

Note :

  • 2 outliers in the leukocyte counts (99 and 100000, respectively)
  • 1 outlier in protein (12000)
  • 1 potential outlier in lactate ?

3. marginalization ¶

A first run of linear models shows that the outliers do have an important effect on the regressions.

The first step should therefore be to exclude them while computing the effect of age and sex:

3.1 removing outliers ¶

In [15]:
df_merged_no_outliers = df_merged.copy()
In [16]:

df_merged_no_outliers.loc['NC040',"CSF_protein"] = np.nan

df_merged_no_outliers["CSF_lactate_log"] = np.log10(df_merged_no_outliers.CSF_lactate)

df_merged["CSF_lactate_log"] = np.log10(df_merged.CSF_lactate)

import statsmodels.api as sm
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf

order5 = ['healthy control','inflammatory control','I','II','III']


## thankfully, the global median value is plausible for all categories (ie. close the the group medians and observed points)
medianAge = df_merged.Age.median() 

ageDiff = df_merged.Age - medianAge
sexDiff = df_merged.Sex == 'm'
In [21]:
marginalizedVals = {}

measures = [ "CSF_leukocytes","CSF_lactate","CSF_protein","CSF_blood_albumin_ratio","CSF_glucose",
           "CSF_leukocytes_log" , "CSF_protein_log","CSF_blood_albumin_ratio_log", "CSF_lactate_log"]

for molec in measures:
    results = smf.ols(molec+' ~ Age + Sex + Stage', data=df_merged_no_outliers).fit()

    ## using the model parameters to marginalize
    diffReference = sexDiff*results.params['Sex[T.m]'] + ageDiff*results.params['Age']

    marginalizedValues = df_merged[molec] - diffReference
    
    marginalizedVals[molec] = marginalizedValues

    # Creating a report of the model and marginalization as a pdf
    fig = plt.figure( figsize=(14,28) )

    gs = fig.add_gridspec(4,2)
    ax1 = fig.add_subplot(gs[0, :]) # ols report
    ax2 = fig.add_subplot(gs[1, 0]) # fitted vs residuals
    ax3 = fig.add_subplot(gs[1, 1]) # fitted vs. observed
    ax4 = fig.add_subplot(gs[2, 0]) # marginalization effect
    ax5 = fig.add_subplot(gs[2, 1]) # histogram observed, marginalization
    ax6 = fig.add_subplot(gs[3, 0]) # boxplot observed
    ax7 = fig.add_subplot(gs[3, 1]) # boxplot marginalized



    ## reporting
    ax1.text( 0,0, str( results.summary() ) , font='monospace' )
    ax1.set_title( molec )
    ax1.axis('off')


    ax2.plot( results.fittedvalues, results.resid ,'o')
    ax2.axhline(0)
    ax2.set_xlabel('fitted values')
    ax2.set_ylabel('residuals')

    ax3.plot( results.fittedvalues, results.resid+results.fittedvalues ,'o')
    m = min(results.fittedvalues)
    M = max(results.fittedvalues)
    ax3.plot( [m,M] , [m,M] , color='red')
    ax3.set_xlabel('fitted values')
    ax3.set_ylabel('observed values')


    ax4.hist(diffReference)
    ax4.set_xlabel("marginalization effect")

    #ax5.hist( marginalizedValues , alpha = 0.5 , label="observed")
    #ax5.hist( df_merged[molec] , color='red', alpha = 0.5, label='marginalized')
    #ax5.set_xlabel(molec)
    #ax5.legend()
    m = min(df_merged[molec])
    M = max(df_merged[molec])
    ax5.scatter(df_merged[molec],marginalizedValues)
    ax5.plot( [m,M] , [m,M] , color='red')
    ax5.set_xlabel( "observed values" )
    ax5.set_xlabel( "marginalized values" )


    sns.boxplot( x="Stage" , y = molec , data=df_merged , ax = ax6  , order = order5 , palette = palette5)

    sns.boxplot( x="Stage" , y = marginalizedValues , data=df_merged , ax = ax7  , order = order5 , palette = palette5)
    ax7.set_ylabel("marginalized values")

    fig.savefig("images/marginalization/neuroCOVID/Clinical_measure_"+molec+"_marginalization_report.pdf")
    #plt.close()

3.3 Summary of marginalization results ¶

The raw data was marginalized to account for discrepancies in the distribution of age and sex between group and reduce the effect of these variables using linear models, similar to what was done on the molecular data, with the following addenda.

  • CSF_glucose : no additionnal note
  • CSF_lactate :
    • patient NC040 was skewing the fit so it was excluded from the model (the data point remains, we only prevented it to skew the marginalization)
    • the data was log10-transformed to avoid heteroskedascticity
  • CSF_blood_albumin_ratio:
    • the data was log10-transformed to avoid heteroskedascticity
  • CSF_protein:
    • patient NC040 was skewing the fit so it was excluded from the model
    • the data was log10-transformed to avoid heteroskedascticity
  • CSF_leukocytes:
    • patients NC040 and 5977 were skewing the fit so they were excluded from the model
    • log10-transformation: actually a log10(0.1 + raw value ) (presence of a 0.0 value in raw data)
    • even after log10-transformation the linear model was deemed inappropriate for this measurement.
    • we recommend not using the marginalized data here, and being very careful about conclusions. Nevertheless keeping the log10 transform looks like a good idea (at least for data representations)

visual representation of the data kept after marginalization (ie. all marginalized except for leukocytes)¶

4.2. testing marginalization ¶

df_merged.rename(columns={'Glucose quotient (CSF/plasma)':'CSF_plasma_glucose_ratio'}, inplace=True)
In [39]:
import statsmodels.api as sm
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf

order5 = ['healthy control','CNS inflammatory','I','II','III']


## thankfully, the global median value is plausible for all categories (ie. close the the group medians and observed points)
medianAge = df_merged.Age.median() 

ageDiff = df_merged.Age - medianAge
sexDiff = df_merged.Sex == 'm'


marginalizedVals = {}


molec='CSF_plasma_glucose_ratio'

results = smf.ols(molec+' ~ Age + Sex + Stage', data=df_merged).fit()

## using the model parameters to marginalize
diffReference = sexDiff*results.params['Sex[T.m]'] + ageDiff*results.params['Age']

marginalizedValues = df_merged[molec] - diffReference

marginalizedVals[molec] = marginalizedValues

# Creating a report of the model and marginalization as a pdf
fig = plt.figure( figsize=(14,28) )

gs = fig.add_gridspec(4,2)
ax1 = fig.add_subplot(gs[0, :]) # ols report
ax2 = fig.add_subplot(gs[1, 0]) # fitted vs residuals
ax3 = fig.add_subplot(gs[1, 1]) # fitted vs. observed
ax4 = fig.add_subplot(gs[2, 0]) # marginalization effect
ax5 = fig.add_subplot(gs[2, 1]) # histogram observed, marginalization
ax6 = fig.add_subplot(gs[3, 0]) # boxplot observed
ax7 = fig.add_subplot(gs[3, 1]) # boxplot marginalized



## reporting
ax1.text( 0,0, str( results.summary() ) , font='monospace' )
ax1.set_title( molec )
ax1.axis('off')


ax2.plot( results.fittedvalues, results.resid ,'o')
ax2.axhline(0)
ax2.set_xlabel('fitted values')
ax2.set_ylabel('residuals')

ax3.plot( results.fittedvalues, results.resid+results.fittedvalues ,'o')
m = min(results.fittedvalues)
M = max(results.fittedvalues)
ax3.plot( [m,M] , [m,M] , color='red')
ax3.set_xlabel('fitted values')
ax3.set_ylabel('observed values')


ax4.hist(diffReference)
ax4.set_xlabel("marginalization effect")

#ax5.hist( marginalizedValues , alpha = 0.5 , label="observed")
#ax5.hist( df_merged[molec] , color='red', alpha = 0.5, label='marginalized')
#ax5.set_xlabel(molec)
#ax5.legend()
m = min(df_merged[molec])
M = max(df_merged[molec])
ax5.scatter(df_merged[molec],marginalizedValues)
ax5.plot( [m,M] , [m,M] , color='red')
ax5.set_xlabel( "observed values" )
ax5.set_xlabel( "marginalized values" )


sns.boxplot( x="Stage" , y = molec , data=df_merged , ax = ax6  , order = order5 , palette = palette5)

sns.boxplot( x="Stage" , y = marginalizedValues , data=df_merged , ax = ax7  , order = order5 , palette = palette5)
ax7.set_ylabel("marginalized values")

fig.savefig("images/Clinical_measure_"+molec+"_marginalization_report.pdf")

So, a very marginal effect of age and sex might be present. The marginalization of data is interesting.

marginalization conclusion :¶

  • marginalization of glucose ratio required the exclusion of outlier 5904 from the model (the data is kept)
  • marginalization effect is likely to be minimal
